  "method": "We propose Composable Discrete Abstractions (CoDA), a neuro-symbolic pipeline that learns a library of discrete, reusable components and composes them with typed operators to solve novel combinations. Perception-side, CoDA factors raw inputs into object-centric slots and induces atom codebooks for objects, attributes, and relations via a vector-quantized bottleneck. Each slot emits top-k atom codes per predicate type; codes are grounded to pixels (or tokens/spans) and to language using multi-task supervision. To stabilize semantics and promote reuse, we cluster occurrences for each code and keep medoid exemplars as the code’s canonical prototypes; the resulting component library pairs each discrete code with medoid evidence and lexical aliases. We maintain a typed scene graph (JSON) whose nodes reference code IDs and medoids, with edges for relations and attributes.\n\nGrounding is trained with three complementary signals: (i) VQ commit/reconstruction on slot features to induce discrete atoms; (ii) supervised grounding using question–segmentation links so each atom aligns to concrete evidence; and (iii) weak supervision from scene-graph parses of captions to encourage consistent atom usage across language and vision. A contrastive alignment loss ties codes to their textual aliases, and a sparsity/capacity regularizer encourages one code per attribute type per slot while allowing polysemy via top-k selection. This turns entangled embeddings into a small vocabulary of typed, evidence-backed atoms that remain reusable across examples and tasks.\n\nReasoning-side, CoDA defines a library of typed, parameterized operators (skills) that transform the discrete scene graph. Each operator declares preconditions over atom codes and predicts postconditions and costs via a learned Skill Effect Model (SEM). Given a current JSON state, an SEM takes operator parameters (e.g., which object-code pair and relation-code to change) and predicts the next JSON state and execution cost. At inference, we plan in operator space using Weighted A*: successors come from instantiating operators over currently bound codes, SEMs score feasibility and cost, and search produces a sequence of operator applications that compose atoms to meet a goal.\n\nTo interface naturally with open-ended tasks, CoDA wraps the planner in a logic-guided controller. A language model translates the user query into a Prolog-style goal with facts derived from the current JSON scene graph, proposes operator applications as clauses, and simulates backtracking traces. The controller maintains and updates the JSON world state explicitly after each operator via an update routine, enabling long-horizon reasoning, replanning, and faithful intermediate structure without depending on an external symbolic engine; the logic trace and the JSON state co-evolve during problem solving.\n\nTraining proceeds in alternating phases: (1) perceptual grounding and code learning (VQ + grounding + contrastive alignment) using paired vision–language data and question–segmentation supervision; (2) operator/SEM training from demonstrations or logged executions by minimizing state-delta and cost prediction losses on the discrete JSON graphs; and (3) joint fine-tuning where planner rollouts supply additional weak labels for rarely seen atoms/relations. Evaluation follows a systematic compositional protocol with Seen vs Unseen Compounds and Unseen Atoms splits to verify that performance stems from recombining learned atoms rather than memorizing compounds.",
  "rationale": "Discrete, typed atom codebooks turn continuous, entangled features into a reusable vocabulary that can be bound, substituted, and recombined. Grounding these codes to concrete evidence (segments/tokens) and stabilizing them with medoid prototypes yields components that are interpretable, shareable across tasks, and resilient to drift. A small operator library with learned effect models gives the system the right granularity for reuse: operators are independent of specific compounds and act on typed codes, so planning over operators composes atoms systematically.\n\nA logic-guided controller that writes and executes Prolog-style traces over an explicit JSON world state enforces faithful, stepwise composition and affords backtracking when novel combinations require exploration. By searching in operator space with SEM costs, the system retains statistical robustness while preserving discrete structure. Systematic evaluation on splits that hold out compounds or atoms ensures the learned atoms and operators genuinely support compositional generalization rather than shortcutting via continuous entanglement.",
