  "method": "We propose learning a compact library of discrete, reusable \"atoms\" and a lightweight reasoning layer that composes them. Concretely, we insert a prototype layer over a backbone encoder that maps inputs to feature maps. The layer maintains K trainable prototypes and computes cosine similarities between features and prototypes with an exponential sharpening to produce peaky affinities. We open S slots and assign features to slots with attention; each slot then selects one prototype via a straight-through Gumbel-Softmax, yielding S discrete atom IDs plus slot-specific attributes (e.g., pooled features conditioned on the chosen prototype). The active atoms and their attributes are emitted as a small set of symbolic tokens. A typed, sparsely connected AtomGraph is formed on these tokens, and a small graph transformer performs the downstream reasoning.\n\nTo make atoms disentangled and reusable, training couples three signals. First, a distinction-maximization loss over the prototype layer pushes prototypes to be discriminative and confident, and a single-pass uncertainty head scores how well each slot is explained by its chosen prototype, with a dedicated \"unknown\" bucket. Second, a mix-and-separate augmentation enforces additivity and separability: we synthetically mix pairs of inputs (or factorized views) and require that the active atom set approximates the union of the two originals and that per-slot decoders can reconstruct masked targets for each component when given only its atoms, while discouraging cross-talk between slots. Third, hard-discreteness is promoted with entropy and exclusivity regularizers over slot assignments and a coverage term that rewards explaining most input evidence with few atoms.\n\nWe structure the atom library hierarchically and modularly. During training, a group-sparse regularizer ranks and prunes prototype-to-module connections, automatically deriving compact sub-libraries specialized for perceptual factors (objects, parts, attributes) and relational factors (spatial, causal). This hierarchical screening stabilizes selection and encourages reuse of a small, tailored set of atoms per subtask. To transfer across domains or tasks without re-entangling, we factor the atom prior into shared and domain-specific components: a shared prior encourages reuse of universal atoms, while lightweight domain-specific priors gate a subset of atoms when context indicates domain shifts, enabling adaptation without altering the shared library.\n\nFor reasoning over novel combinations, we operate only on the top-M confident atoms selected by a tiny selector (a shallow scorer over atom IDs and attributes), keeping compute low and reducing spurious interactions. The AtomGraph uses typed edges (e.g., object–attribute, object–object–relation) with a small number of learnable relation types and optional parent nodes that summarize coarse-grained atoms, letting the graph transformer aggregate evidence and apply reusable patterns over symbol IDs rather than raw features. Supervised objectives (task loss) backpropagate through the graph to the atoms; auxiliary consistency checks enforce that reordering or substituting atoms in held-out combinations yields predictable changes in outputs, directly training for compositional generalization.\n\nAt inference, the model emits a discrete set of atom IDs with attributes, an uncertainty score per slot, and a reasoning trace over the AtomGraph. High-uncertainty slots fall back to parent atoms or are masked, preserving robustness. Because the reasoning operates over a small, typed, reusable vocabulary, it generalizes to unseen combinations by recombining known atoms and relations rather than relearning entangled continuous codes.",
  "rationale": "Discrete prototype selection ensures that the same few atoms are reused across many inputs, turning entangled features into a symbolic vocabulary. The distinction-maximization and entropy/exclusivity losses make these atoms sharp and non-overlapping, while the uncertainty head prevents forcing bad assignments. The mix-and-separate training pressure explicitly teaches the model that factors add and can be pulled apart, a key ingredient for making atoms independent and composable rather than fused.\n\nOrganizing the library with hierarchical, group-sparse screening yields small, specialized sub-libraries that are easier to reuse and compose. Shared vs domain-specific priors further protect reusability by separating what should transfer from what should adapt. Finally, casting reasoning as message passing over a typed graph of atom IDs converts continuous entanglement into discrete structure; the lightweight selector and parent nodes keep the graph compact and stable, letting the same relation types fire over novel atom combinations and thereby deliver compositional generalization.",
